  1. Setting the df "top1000" to be equal to the columns listed
  2. sorting them in descending order by rating
  3. dropping the duplicate names (players in this dataset had multiple versions)
  4. taking the first 1000 rows of the sorted data
  5. changing the column names to be more interpretable
  6. showing the top 10 rows as a sample
In [3]:
top1000 = ps4[['name', 'rating', 'position', 'price', 'league', 'team', 'country', 'PAC', 'SHO', 'PAS', 'DRI', 'PHY', 'DEF']] \
.sort_values(by = 'rating', ascending = False) \
.drop_duplicates(subset = 'name') \
.head(1000)

top1000.columns = ['name', 'rating', 'position', 'price', 'league', 'team', 'country', 'pace', 'shooting', 'passing', 'dribbling', 'physical', 'defence']
top1000.reset_index(inplace = True, drop = True)

"""
This way of looking at data gives a small/quick way to try to establish relationships between different variables.
The diagonal where both x and y are the same are shown as histograms.

WARNING! Make sure that you are only passing through small subsets of your data. Even for only 1,000 players and a few
numeric columns, this plot is huge and took about 20 seconds to load. Upping the amount of rows or columns here 
can increase that time dramatically. 
"""

sns.pairplot(data = top1000);

In [7]:
"""
A histogram of the ratings of the top 1000 players in Fifa 19.
Color arbitrarily set to dark red. It shows the data above, and
also it is important to note that the line here is the 'kernel
density estimate' or KDE. this is a default in seaborn, it also
messes with the y axis and it shows the probability density 
of a random variable occuring ("The odds that I randomly pick a 
90 rated player out of my pile of 1000 is roughly %2.5 per our KDE)
"""
sns.distplot(top1000.rating, color = 'darkred')

In [9]:
"""
Here, I show how to iterate through a list of colors and a list of countries.
Making a histogram of various countries on the same plot. the for loop moves
through the list of countries (and count is increased as a part of that loop).
Here, I show the histogram of the ratings for each country with 10 bins. The
countries and colors are both placed in order here. Something similar to this can
also be accomplished with a dictionary. Also, note that KDE is set to off here
and your y axis is in an actual count... "There are 27 players in France
rated between 78 and 80, 5 Belgians rated 82-84, and 1 Colombian rated 88-90."
"""

colorlist = ['blue', 'darkred', 'gold']
count = 0
for ctry in ['France', 'Belgium', 'Colombia']:
    sns.distplot(a = top1000[top1000.country == ctry]['rating'], color = colorlist[count], bins = [78, 80, 82, 84, 86, 88, 90, 92], kde = False)
    count+=1

"""
This section peels off only strikers/attackers from Brazil with unique ratings.
(Note: There can't be two strikers with the same rating in our dataset, you can confirm this below...)
Then makes some quick bar charts. The colors here are meant only to evoke the idea of Brazil and
are a showcase of different ways to manipulate palettes and colors in Seaborn, the colors don't 
necessarily make these bar graphs any more useful in their current state.
"""

brazil = top1000[top1000.country == 'Brazil']

The default Seaborn color palette, great for categorical data. You will learn to love these colors and may start recognizing them all over the place.¶

In [14]:
"""
Here as rating goes up on the X, the color will move through the diverging palette we created above
here, pace is what is on the y axis.
"""

sns.barplot(data = brazilstrikers, x = 'rating', y = 'pace', hue = 'rating', palette=brazpalette);
In [15]:
"""
Here, we are dropping colors into a new palette both by name and by hex value (see the last
item in the list). Here, it is important that the number of colors MATCHES the number of objects
we are going to use this palette on. 7 colors? 7 bars, otherwise it may yell at you. You can use 
palettes from seaborn without worrying about how many items they're going to be applied to,
but when you are creating a custom list of colors, it may be slightly more particular.
"""

brazpalette2 = sns.color_palette(['green', 'lightgreen', 'blue', 'skyblue', 'yellow', 'gold', '#2ecc71'])
sns.palplot(brazpalette2)
In [16]:
"""
Here are some more colors that are similar to the brazilian flag from the palette we made above.
Notice that they are applied in the same order that they were put into the list above.
"""

sns.barplot(data = brazilstrikers, x = 'rating', y = 'dribbling', hue = 'rating', palette=brazpalette2);
In [17]:
"""
Here is an example where we passed through a hue and a color. So the color is used as a seed
for the color gradient that will be applied. It looks like by default it will set that
color as the top of the gradient and white as the bottom. Here, we are using the color to
show the physical stats of a player, effectively adding a new dimension to this graph.
It looks like the 81 rated player, Soares, has the highest physical stat of our group and
therefore the darkest gold color.
"""

sns.barplot(data = brazilstrikers, x = 'rating', y = 'shooting', hue = 'physical', color = 'gold');

Some Diverging palettes looking at italian soccer players¶

In [24]:
"""
These next few plots check rating against defense for Italy while using an italian-looking color palette called 'RdYlGn'. You
can see the way that it's reversed in the line of code below with 3 colors so that it looks like an Italian flag.
The first and second plots are identical with the exception of the hue value. You can see in the first plot that the rating (which
is on the X axis) was used for hue, this means that as you went up the x axis you'd move from red to green. The second plot does the
opposite. That palette moves up on the y axis. The third plot merely reverses the palette (RdYlGn Vs. RdYlGn_r). Quite a few different
things can be done with diverging color palettes.
"""

sns.palplot(sns.color_palette('RdYlGn', n_colors = 10))
In [25]:
sns.palplot(sns.color_palette('RdYlGn_r', n_colors = 3))

Joint Distribution Plots¶

In [35]:
"""
These two plots are fun to use as they add a flourish on top of scatter plots and show the density in an interesting
and interpretable way. The first one just gets a color parameter and guesses a palette around it and is used to show
a comparison between physical and defensive stats. The second gets a color change to the very interesting "gist_earth"
colormap and becomes an island. It is a purely aesthetic change. Finally, the third plot gets a change from the
KDE plot to a hex-bin plot. So densities are shown in hexagon-shaped pixels rather than the kernel density function
over the space, this seems to make this chart more discrete.
"""

g = sns.jointplot("physical", "defence", data=top1000, kind="kde", color="g", height = 10)
In [36]:
g = sns.jointplot("physical", "defence", data=top1000, kind="kde", cmap='gist_earth', height = 10)
In [38]:
g = sns.jointplot("physical", "defence", data=top1000, kind="hex", cmap='gist_earth', height = 10)
